        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim for a high fidelity, high dynamic range map of the 12CO emission across NGC 253.

SPECTRAL SETUP: We tile two high spectral resolution (&lt; 0.5 km/s) windows on the 12CO 1-0 line, our main goal. Together they cover the galaxy and still allow us to heavily resolve even a narrow molecular cloud (line width a few km/s). We allocate the remaining two spectral windows to the CN and C17O lines, which are targets of secondary stacking science (enabled by the ACA).

BAND CHOICE: We need the most agnostic bright tracer of molecular gas, including unexcited, faint gas. 12CO 1-0 represents the only viable choice.

DATA RATE: We set a factor of two spectral binning for all windows and so do not exceed the data rate cap.

MOSAIC: We position a 7.25 x 3 arcminute mosaic to cover the bar, nuclear starburst, arms, and interarm region. The coverage illustration in the main text shows the appropriateness of the choice. We adopt the recommended field spacing.

RESOLUTION: We aim to reach scales matched to the size of an individual ISM cloud and target 3" = 50 pc at the 3.5 Mpc distance of NGC 253, a typical radius for a Galactic or nearby galaxy GMC.

ACA: Our goal is a high fidelity, high dynamic range map that will let us probe diffuse - the ACA is absolutely essential. NGC 253 is large on the sky with extended emission and we wish to test for the presence of a diffuse emission component.

SENSITIVITY: We target 0.1 K, motivated by the desire to recover the full range of molecular cloud and to probe even faint ISM components. This maps to a S/N 5 point source sensitivity of LCO~5e3 K km/s pc^2, about the luminosity of a low mass star forming cloud like Taurus or Perseus and more than 10x fainter than Orion. We also recover CO at S/N &gt; 5 everywhere that Sigma_H2 &gt; 10 Msun/pc2, i.e., everywhere that H2 makes up a significant fraction of the ISM.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
