    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to use ALMA to make a high fidelity, high dynamic range map of the molecular ISM across the Sculptor Galaxy with the goal of studying the ISM's detailed structure in a star-forming spiral galaxy. This is crucial to understand the formation of GMCs and the regulation of star formation in galaxies. The very nearby Sculptor Galaxy (NGC 253, d=3.5Mpc) offers a wide range of star-forming environments in a single large mosaic: a bar, spiral arms, interarm star formation, and a nuclear starburst. In each environment, we will combine the brightness distribution, cloud property measurements, and image statistics to quantitatively characterize ISM structure. Together these approaches will constraint the prevalence and structure of any faint, extended CO component; the column density, volume density, and cloud mass distributions; and GMC scaling (Larson) relations. We will link variations in ISM structure back to the overall ability of gas in each environment to form stars. This project is possible because of ALMA’s unique ability to build sensitive, high fidelity, high dynamic range images over large areas – a capability as new and important as its phenomenal spectroscopic power.</prp:abstract>
